The provinces of the east present the contrast of Roman magnificence with Turkish barbarism. The ruins of antiquity scattered over un- cultivated fields, and ascribed, by ignorance, to the power of magio, scarcely afford a shelter to the oppressed peasant or wan- dering Arab.
